Understanding the difference between these two groups matters for rational platform selection. A cost minimalist with $50,000 in savings should prioritize Schwab's zero-fee model — saving $125 per year versus a 0.25% platform compounds into **$8,400+ over 30 years** at 7% annual growth. However, investors should factor in Schwab's cash drag: a 10% mandatory cash allocation on that same $50,000 means $5,000 earning bank deposit rates instead of equity returns, effectively costing more than the "saved" advisory fee in many market environments. Conversely, a high-income earner in the 37% federal tax bracket benefits far more from Wealthfront's daily TLH engine, which can generate **$1,800+ in annual tax savings** on a $100,000 portfolio — dwarfing the $250 management fee. The right choice depends on your marginal tax rate, portfolio size, and whether you value transparent pricing over headline-zero costs.

