### Betterment

As the original robo-advisor (founded 2008), Betterment has had more time than any competitor to refine its portfolio construction methodology. The platform's most significant technical distinction is its use of the Black-Litterman model — a Bayesian framework that starts with market-equilibrium expected returns (derived from the global market portfolio) and adjusts them based on the firm's forward-looking views with calibrated confidence levels. Where standard mean-variance optimization can produce unstable, concentrated portfolios from noisy historical return estimates, Black-Litterman generates more diversified allocations by anchoring to equilibrium and making measured tilts based on posterior probability distributions.

In practice, this means Betterment's portfolios tend to be less sensitive to recent market movements than competitors using purely historical MVO. The platform supports the widest account type coverage in the automated investing space: taxable accounts, traditional and Roth IRAs, SEP IRAs, inherited IRAs, trust accounts, Solo 401(k)s, and joint accounts — more than 10 distinct structures. Tax-loss harvesting runs on all taxable accounts with no minimum balance requirement, and the Tax-Coordinated Portfolio feature optimizes asset location across taxable and tax-advantaged accounts simultaneously, placing tax-inefficient assets (bonds, REITs) in tax-advantaged accounts and tax-efficient holdings (total market ETFs) in taxable accounts.

During our 90-day evaluation, Betterment's TLH module executed harvesting events on 8 separate occasions. The platform recently expanded its offering to include crypto portfolios and three distinct ESG impact-focused portfolio options. At 0.25% annually with no minimum, the core Digital plan competes directly with Wealthfront on price. The Premium tier at 0.65% adds unlimited CFP access for investors who want human guidance layered onto the Bayesian-optimized automation.

