### Acorns

Acorns pioneered the micro-investing category by turning spare change into portfolio contributions. The platform's signature feature links to debit and credit cards, rounding each purchase up to the nearest dollar and automatically investing the difference into a diversified ETF portfolio. A $4.73 coffee becomes a $5.00 charge with $0.27 invested — individually small, but capable of generating $30–60 per month for active spenders without any conscious budgeting effort. The company reports that the average user accumulates over $1,000 in their first year through roundups alone.

Beyond micro-investing, Acorns offers traditional recurring deposits, an Acorns Early custodial account for children, and a checking account with a debit card that earns bonus investments at 350+ partner retailers. The flat-fee pricing ($3/month Personal, $5 Family, $12 Premium) makes Acorns relatively expensive on a percentage basis for small balances — $3/month on a $500 balance equates to a 7.2% annual fee. However, as balances grow past $5,000, that effective rate drops below 0.72%, and the behavioral benefit of automated saving often outweighs the fee differential for investors who struggle with consistency. Portfolio construction uses standard MVO across five preset allocations without tax-loss harvesting or advanced customization.

