### Stash

Stash bridges the gap between robo-advisory and self-directed investing with a hybrid model designed for investors who want to learn by doing. The platform's Smart Portfolios handle automated ETF investing similar to traditional robo-advisors, while a separate DIY section lets users purchase fractional shares of individual stocks and thematic ETFs organized into plain-language categories. This dual structure appeals to a specific investor persona: someone who wants automated diversification as a foundation but also wants to experiment with individual picks without opening a separate brokerage account.

Stash's educational layer reinforces this positioning — every stock and ETF listing includes a risk rating, plain-English description, and relevant news, turning each investment decision into a learning opportunity. The Stock-Back debit card awards fractional shares of companies where you shop (0.125% at most retailers, up to 5% at select partners). At $3/month for Growth or $9/month for Stash+, the flat pricing hurts small portfolios but becomes reasonable above $5,000. Our testing found the educational content genuinely useful for newer investors, though the automated portfolio options are more limited (three risk levels) than dedicated robo-advisors.

